<DOC><DOCNO> AP890909-0097 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1541EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Guerrillas     09-09 0221</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Guerrillas,0228</SECOND><HEAD>Tribal Guerrillas Kill 12</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Separatist guerrillas raided a remoteborder village in northeastern India and killed 12 people, PressTrust of India reported Saturday.   Friday night's attack by militants of the Bodo tribe also left atleast 27 people injured in the village of Bokajali in Assam state,the news agency said. The village is about 800 miles east of NewDelhi.   The agency said all the victims were native Assamese whose houseswere burned in the raid.   The latest deaths bring to 20 the number of people killed in thepast week by Bodo guerrillas fighting for a separate homeland inAssam, a hilly state bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan.   Police are searching nearby forests where the attackers arebelieved to have fled, Press Trust said.   Bodo militants pressed their demands for more than 20 years, thentook up arms two years ago. At least 270 people have been killed inthe violence this year.   The government refuses to consider their tribal demand, but heldunsuccessful peace talks last year with militants who allege theyare discriminated against by the state's majority Assamese people.   Bodos are mostly farmers who were animists before they convertedearlier this century to Christianity and Hindusim, India's dominantreligion. They are 30 percent of Assam's 20 million people.</TEXT></DOC>